I"ý<p>People are capable of adjusting their baseline reference point of pain and pleasure based on experience. This means that through long enough exposure to a pleasant or painful stimuli, one is going to eventually <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/perception-is-context-dependent">perceive it as perfectly ordinary</a>. <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/apathy-is-hedonic-adaptation-to-dreadful-situations">Hedonic adaptation also empowers individuals going through difficult situations</a>. The biological substrate of hedonic adaptation appears to me linked to the highly adaptive nature of <a class="internal-link" href="/secondbrain/biological-reward-systems-are-malleable">reward systems</a>, which aggressively habituate past rewards.</p>
